# Performance Standards

- This is a stack-specific rule file for Node.js runtime behavior.
- Optimize only after identifying the hot path, bottleneck, or operational limit being addressed.
- Keep execution paths non-blocking where possible. Avoid CPU-heavy work, large synchronous loops, and blocking I/O in shared transport helpers.
- For large payloads or long-running transfers, prefer stream-aware handling and bounded buffering over unbounded accumulation.
- Reuse shared serializers, validators, and transport helpers on hot paths instead of rebuilding equivalent logic per feature.
- Avoid accidental quadratic work in node execution code, response normalizers, serializers, and mappers when processing rows or chunks.
- Enforce the documented `PayloadFrame` guardrails: size checks, inflation ratio limits, and explicit chunk aggregation behavior.
- When a change targets performance-sensitive behavior, document the assumption being optimized and verify the result with measurement or profiling.
